A keylogger is a machine that assists which grammar and spelling. It predicts the words you are trying to write and completes them for you
A keylogger is a piece of software that stores your passwords so you don’t have to remember them
A keylogger refers to the malicious action of recording input made via a keyboard without the user knowing. This way passwords or messages can be restored
A keylogger is someone who edits the inputs made via a keyboard. This is most commonly used to make users visit fraudulent websites they didn’t intend to visit

In a denial of service attack the attacker puts up a fake duplication of a legitimate website. He replaces the original website with an error message prompting the user to visit the new, malicious, website

In a denial of service attack an attacker tells users that their internet is currently unavailable due to a system fault. Most users believe this and follow the attacker’s invitation to a fraudulent repair service asking for personal and financial information
A denial of service attack refers to an attack made by a large number of fake visits to a website. This causes the website to crash resulting in a “denial of service”
